The mpg data frame

  • Let’s start with the mpg data frame found in ggplot2 (aka ggplot2::mpg).
  • mpg contains observations collected by the US Environment Protection Agency on 38 models of cars.

Questions

  • Do cars with big engines use more fuel than cars with small engines?
  • What does the relationship between engine size and fuel efficiency look like? Is it positive? Negative? Linear? Nonlinear?

Among the variables in mpg are:

  1. displ, a car’s engine size, in litres.

  2. hwy, a car’s fuel efficiency on the highway, in miles per gallon (mpg). A car with a low fuel efficiency consumes more fuel than a car with a high fuel efficiency when they travel the same distance.

Creating a ggplot

To plot mpg, run this code to put displ on the x-axis and hwy on the y-axis:

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

What do we learn?

  • Begin a plot with the function ggplot().
    • ggplot() creates a coordinate system that you can add layers to.
    • The first argument of ggplot() is the dataset to use in the graph.
  • Complete your graph by adding one or more layers to ggplot().
  • The function geom_point() adds a layer of points to your plot.
  • geom function takes a mapping argument: how variables in your dataset are mapped to visual properties.
  • The mapping argument is always paired with aes().

A graphing template

ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))

Mappings

  • In the plot below, one group of points seems to fall outside of the linear trend. How are they different?
  • How can you explain these cars?

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class))

(If you prefer British English, like Hadley, you can use colour instead of color.)

There are more than one mapping

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

Notes

  • We mapped class to the color (or colour depending on your preference), alpha, shape aesthetics.
  • Sometimes one aesthetic is better than the other! Consider size asthetic. What do you think?

Facets

  • For categorical variables facets can be useful.
  • To facet your plot by a single variable, use facet_wrap().
    • facet_wrap() should have a formula; ~ followed by a variable name.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

Facets

  • To facet your plot on the combination of two variables, add facet_grid().
    • The first argument of facet_grid() is also a formula.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

How are these two plots similar?

Geometric objects

  • Both plots
    • contain the same \(x\) variable
    • contain the same \(y\) variable,
    • describe the same data
  • But the plots are not identical–each plot uses a different visual object to represent the data.
  • They use different geoms.

geom

  • A geom is the geometrical object that a plot uses to represent data.
    • bar charts use bar geoms
    • line charts use line geoms
    • boxplots use boxplot geoms
    • …
  • One uses the point geom, and the other uses the smooth geom.
  • To change the geom in your plot, change the geom function that you add to ggplot().
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

More on geom

  • Not every aesthetic works with every geom
    • You could set the shape of a point, but you couldn’t set the “shape” of a line.
ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                            linetype = drv))

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, 
                                 color = drv)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(linetype = drv))

Multiple geoms in the same plot

To display multiple geoms in the same plot, add multiple geom functions to ggplot():

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Global mappings

You can pass a set of mappings to ggplot():

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_smooth()

Local vs Global

  • If you place mappings in a geom function, ggplot2 will treat them as local mappings for the layer.
  • These mappings will extend or overwrite the global mappings for that layer only.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth()

joining different datasets

  • You can specify different data for each layer; our smooth line displays just a subset of the mpg dataset, the subcompact cars.
  • The local data argument in geom_smooth() overrides the global data argument in ggplot() for that layer only.
ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) + 
  geom_smooth(data = filter(mpg, class == "subcompact"),
              se = FALSE)

diamonds data set

  • Dataset comes in ggplot2 and contains information about ~54,000 diamonds
    • price, carat, color, clarity, and cut.
  • More diamonds are available with high quality cuts than with low quality cuts.

Thought process

ggplot(data = <DATA>) + 
  <GEOM_FUNCTION>(mapping = aes(<MAPPINGS>))
  • aes?
    • x-axis?: cut.
    • y-axis?: count.
  • geom?:
    • geom_bar
  • Do we have count in the data set?
    • we need to calculate new values to plot.

Workflow

voilà!

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut))

Saving the plot

test_plot <- ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut))
ggsave("test_plot.png") # for png file
ggsave("test_plot.pdf") # for pdf file
